IMF needs more Lagarde
Davos—Lagarde has said that she is open to serving another five years as head of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
She should remain.
The IMF has never had a better leadership than under her; the IMF's Board of Governors should give her the chance to complete the work she herself set in motion.
Lagarde took over in July 2011, inheriting a crisis-stricken institution.
2008年全球金融大崩盘及其经济余波让西方领导的多边贷款机构和自由市场“华盛顿共识”信誉扫地。
Under Lagarde's leadership, the IMF restored its reputation.
许多人的眼光投向了她的个人品质——理应如此。
她坦诚、有力、温暖且动人。
与她会面的各国官员（往往是在微妙的环境中会面）表示，她敢于直言不讳，同时也是一位敏感的倾听者。
These are important qualities for an institution leader who must negotiate terms rather than dictate them.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed to be recapitalized or firewalled against financial contagion – hard truths they took to heart.
Similarly, she was vocal about providing IMF support to countries like Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine – crucial for global stability.
There are countless other examples.
IMF is not known for innovation, nor is it typically passionate.
Lagarde began changing this.
In the process, she gave the institution known for tough medicine a face of human compassion.
For example, managing the refugee crisis in the Middle East was not traditionally part of the IMF’s mandate.
But under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its plans to allow the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to help those displaced by the conflicts in Syria and Iraq (over one million refugees live in camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak struck West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF to use its available resources to provide debt relief to affected countries, enabling them to improve the pay of doctors and nurses – a first for the fund to use its capital in this way.
Additionally, Lagarde recognized three of the most important challenges facing the world today and acted on them.
First, she forcefully advocated for greater female participation in the labor force, being a role model of the value of women in leadership positions.
In countries ranging from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urged leaders to stop wasting such vast talent resources — and thus realize economic potential.
Second, under her leadership, the IMF also addressed income inequality, a broader issue.
This is not just a basic fairness issue.
IMF research emphasizes the direct link between reducing income inequality and boosting growth.
While other institutions have demonstrated this point, the IMF's stature makes it particularly pressing.
Individually, Lagarde has been a key proponent of this, driving up its urgency.
Third, Lagarde played a significant role in helping the world recognize the full impact of technological change — some of which will have frighteningly destructive effects.
For instance, automation will continue to increase the efficiency and reduce the costs of manufacturing, but it also means fewer jobs will be created as a result of growth compared to before.
<s>This emerging reality's political, economic, and social consequences are worth recognizing and studying seriously.
<s>Lagarde made the IMF central to this work.
<s>Critics might say it is time for developing countries' representatives to lead the IMF.
<s>After all, Lagarde is the eleventh European to hold this position, and Europe's having such privilege is hard to justify in today's world.
<s>Some might argue that the austerity imposed on Greece by the IMF did not yield the desired results, proving that she is out of touch with ordinary people.
<s>还有一些人会指出，她面临与法国的金融丑闻有关的指控，这将让她从IMF的工作中分心。
<s>在她的前任多米尼克·斯特劳斯-卡恩（Dominique Strauss-Kahn）深陷丑闻后，批评者认为IMF决不能再一次因类似的事件而分心。
<s>我们来逐个分析这些反对意见。
<s>IMF（以及世界银行）应该欢迎来自欧洲和美国之外的领导者。
<s>但结束这一西方特权的目的是让领导者遴选过程以才干而不是政治考虑为基础。
<s>La Garde is the best person to lead the IMF, and emerging powers such as the BRICS (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) have not united to nominate a replacement.
<s>Picking an IMF chief from Europe may have been one reason why the IMF decided last December to include the renminbi in the basket of currencies used to determine the value of its special drawing rights.
<s>Moreover, La Garde's impressive political flexibility finally persuaded both Republicans and Democrats in the US Congress to approve IMF governance reforms that not only bolstered the IMF's arsenal against financial crises but also more accurately reflected the evolving global economic dynamics.
<s>For example, now the BRICS are among the IMF's top ten shareholders.
<s>Last year, La Garde made some characteristically forthright – and possibly inappropriate – comments on Greece.
But she is not the architect of Greece's economic suffering: her tenure at the IMF fully demonstrates that no IMF chief in history has done so much to lead the Fund in efforts to alleviate the pain of people caught in crises.
Finally, the French charges against Lagarde were opposed by the French public prosecutor, and she was at most tangentially involved.
The world urgently needs a leader committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has already shown that she is such a leader, committed to adapting the IMF for the 21st century.
She deserves the opportunity to do so from start to finish.
